Yes — `bun test` uses Bun’s own test runner, but it exposes a Jest-compatible API for `expect()`, `describe()`, `test()`, hooks, mocks, etc. Bun documents its test runner as “Jest-compatible” and shows `test`/`expect` being used via `bun:test` or as test-runner syntax. Sources: Bun test runner docs: https://bun.sh/docs/cli/test and `bun:test` API docs: https://bun.sh/docs/test/writing

So you can write Jest-style tests like:

```ts
describe("math", () => {
  test("adds", () => {
    expect(1 + 1).toBe(2);
  });
});
```

